7.8.4.Solution:
 Every vector in $W$ is orthogonal to $v=(a, b, c)$. Let $Q$ be the orthogonal projection of $\mathbb{R}^{3}$ onto the space spanned by $v$, identified with its matrix. The columns of $Q$ are $Q e_{j}, 1 \leqslant j \leqslant 3$, where the $e_{j}$ 's are the standard basis vectors in $\mathbb{R}^{3}$. But

$$
\begin{aligned}
&Q e_{1}=\left\langle v, e_{1}\right\rangle v=\left(a^{2}, a b, a c\right) \\
&Q e_{2}=\left\langle v, e_{2}\right\rangle v=\left(a b, b^{2}, b c\right) \\
&Q e_{3}=\left\langle v, e_{3}\right\rangle v=\left(a c, b c, c^{2}\right) .
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the orthogonal projection onto $W$ is given by

$$
P=I-Q=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
1-a^{2} & -a b & -a c \\
-a b & 1-b^{2} & -b c \\
-a c & -b c & 1-c^{2}
\end{array}\right) \text {. }
$$
